{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659033"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:00:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:00:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20843"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20843"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96412"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13718"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12331"},{"type":"tags","id":"12667"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33028"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33029"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96412"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a major mechanism by which cancer cells evade apoptosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enhanced DNA repair preventing cellular stress","Increased expression of pro-apoptotic BH3-only proteins","Downregulation of anti-apoptotic BCL2 family members","Activation of caspase inhibitors by microRNAs","Loss of TP53 function through mutation or inhibition"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of TP53 function through mutation or inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E is a major mechanism by which cancer cells evade apoptosis. TP53 mutations are common in cancers at diagnosis and even more frequent in tumors that relapse after therapy. When TP53 function is lost, cells cannot upregulate PUMA (a pro-apoptotic BH3-only protein) in response to DNA damage and other stresses, allowing cells to survive that would otherwise undergo apoptosis. TP53 function can also be impaired indirectly through amplification of MDM2, which encodes an inhibitor of p53.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased expression of pro-apoptotic BH3-only proteins\u003C/strong\u003E would promote rather than prevent apoptosis. Cancer cells typically suppress these proteins or their function to evade cell death.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDownregulation of anti-apoptotic BCL2 family members\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because cancer cells often overexpress (not downregulate) anti-apoptotic BCL2 family proteins to protect themselves from apoptosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced DNA repair preventing cellular stress\u003C/strong\u003E may contribute to cancer cell survival but is not one of the two major mechanisms of apoptosis evasion described in the literature.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of caspase inhibitors by microRNAs\u003C/strong\u003E reverses the actual relationship; in some cancers, microRNAs that normally restrain anti-apoptotic proteins like BCL2 are lost, leading to increased expression of these proteins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe second major mechanism by which cancer cells evade apoptosis is overexpression of anti-apoptotic members of the BCL2 family. This can occur through various mechanisms, including chromosomal translocations (as in follicular lymphoma with the t(14;18) translocation) or loss of microRNAs that normally suppress BCL2 expression (as in chronic lymphocytic leukemia).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cancer cells evade apoptosis through two major mechanisms: loss of TP53 function and overexpression of anti-apoptotic BCL2 family proteins.","TP53 mutations are common in cancers at diagnosis and even more frequent in tumors that relapse after therapy.","Overexpression of BCL2 can result from chromosomal translocations, loss of regulatory microRNAs, or other mechanisms that protect cancer cells from apoptosis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; 302-303."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20843"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79061"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T11:24:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T11:25:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13718"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96412"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",